00:15:33.000 --> 00:15:36.470
community, and they've said to us that they don't want this.

250
00:15:36.880 --> 00:15:40.590
For many Maori men, barbershops isn't just a business or

251
00:15:41.400 --> 00:15:45.100
a place to get a haircut. They tell us that it's a place for

252
00:15:45.120 --> 00:15:47.100
whakawhanaungatanga and for connection.

253
00:15:47.289 --> 00:15:50.320
And one of our local barbers said this space is more

254
00:15:51.460 --> 00:15:54.600
than just guys coming to get their monthly haircuts.

255
00:15:54.640 --> 00:15:58.040
It's a place where they can talk and feel safe and be uplifted.

256
00:15:58.680 --> 00:16:01.760
And so we should be protecting these spaces and not

257
00:16:02.100 --> 00:16:04.740
normalizing alcohol within them.

258
00:16:06.100 --> 00:16:09.820
Thirdly, this bill would disproportionately affect communities already

259
00:16:09.880 --> 00:16:11.580
carrying the greatest burden of harm.

260
00:16:12.480 --> 00:16:16.280
For a lot of the whanau that we work with, fetal alcohol spectrum

261
00:16:16.340 --> 00:16:20.200
disorder is something that we see a lot, and

262
00:16:20.280 --> 00:16:23.740
throughout our FASD and whanau support work, we're hearing directly from young

263
00:16:23.800 --> 00:16:26.080
parents living with those challenges.

264
00:16:26.880 --> 00:16:30.620
So to give you an example, at a recent FASD wananga that we

265
00:16:30.680 --> 00:16:34.260
held at our community space, Te Whaipiringa in

266
00:16:34.300 --> 00:16:38.280
GI, in Glen Innes in Tamaki, whanau spoke about alcohol being

267
00:16:38.340 --> 00:16:42.020
much easier to access than counseling in that area, and

268
00:16:42.080 --> 00:16:44.300
support during those difficult periods.

269
00:16:44.380 --> 00:16:48.370
And to give you a quote, one of the mums said to us, "I was going through

270
00:16:48.370 --> 00:16:52.100
a really hard time in my life when I was pregnant, but there was

271
00:16:52.120 --> 00:16:56.020
three bottle stores within walking distance of where I lived, but counseling

272
00:16:56.040 --> 00:16:59.880
was too expensive." So many of those whanau are thankfully

273
00:16:59.960 --> 00:17:03.170
now on their healing journeys and working really hard to create healthier futures

274
00:17:03.240 --> 00:17:06.970
for their tamariki and mokopuna. But we're concerned that this bill will make

275
00:17:07.620 --> 00:17:08.340
their journeys

276
00:17:09.320 --> 00:17:13.200
much harder by increasing the visibility, the accessibility, and

277
00:17:13.210 --> 00:17:16.120
normalization of alcohol in everyday life.

278
00:17:17.080 --> 00:17:20.780
So if the committee chooses to progress this bill, we

279
00:17:21.360 --> 00:17:24.960
really urge that you retain those broad community rights to

280
00:17:25.000 --> 00:17:28.960
object, that the previous submitter has spoken to, but that

281
00:17:29.000 --> 00:17:32.360
there has to be more consideration for iwi and for hapu

282
00:17:32.860 --> 00:17:36.840
like ourselves, who might not have a physical address

283
00:17:36.880 --> 00:17:39.080
within that area, but has active interest.

284
00:17:39.780 --> 00:17:42.280
And to the point around

285
00:17:43.340 --> 00:17:47.100
if you don't live there but want to object and live within two

286
00:17:47.180 --> 00:17:47.760
kilometers,

287
00:17:48.720 --> 00:17:52.700
my question is, what does this mean for-- in the example I've given you of

288
00:17:52.720 --> 00:17:56.480
her kohanga, we've got many whanau who, many

289
00:17:56.520 --> 00:17:59.080
tamariki who live in multiple dwellings.

290
00:17:59.100 --> 00:18:02.950
Some live in other suburbs because their parents might live elsewhere, but

291
00:18:02.980 --> 00:18:06.540
they really wanted to have a say in that objection process.

292
00:18:06.560 --> 00:18:10.340
So what would this mean for them? We also urge that you

293
00:18:10.380 --> 00:18:14.100
protect local alcohol policies as an important expression of community

294
00:18:14.160 --> 00:18:15.680
voice and local decision-making,

295
00:18:16.920 --> 00:18:20.860
and look into those trading hours preventing further expansion into everyday

296
00:18:20.940 --> 00:18:24.400
community spaces. So ultimately, we believe alcohol

297
00:18:24.480 --> 00:18:28.200
policy should be guided by the well-being of our communities and not by the

298
00:18:28.260 --> 00:18:32.160
convenience of the alcohol industrySo I'm willing to take

299
00:18:32.190 --> 00:18:33.930
questions. We've got about three minutes, don't we?

300
00:18:34.590 --> 00:18:37.989
All right. Hey, thanks, Lizzie. Right. Any questions from anyone?

301
00:18:40.670 --> 00:18:44.070
Don't think so. Lizzie, why do you think that you-

302
00:18:44.910 --> 00:18:45.590
Oh, there's a question.

303
00:18:45.610 --> 00:18:47.130
Oh, sorry. I've got a question here.

304
00:18:47.510 --> 00:18:47.910
Yeah.

305
00:18:48.630 --> 00:18:50.240
Miss Kahu Carter.

306
00:18:51.460 --> 00:18:52.180
Go ahead, Rachel.

307
00:18:52.180 --> 00:18:54.190
Kia ora, Lizzie. Thank you so much.

308
00:18:54.290 --> 00:18:56.230
I just wanted to say thank you for

309
00:18:57.250 --> 00:18:58.790
speaking on behalf of Ngā Whare Maha.

310
00:18:58.820 --> 00:19:01.850
I used to be a kaiako there, and my kids went there as well.

311
00:19:01.940 --> 00:19:01.940
Ah.

312
00:19:01.990 --> 00:19:03.730
So, lovely to see whānau.

313
00:19:05.470 --> 00:19:09.350
So, in terms of the whānau living

314
00:19:09.510 --> 00:19:10.100
outside

315
00:19:11.410 --> 00:19:15.230
the territory or the one-kilometer zone,

316
00:19:16.370 --> 00:19:17.530
do you think that

317
00:19:18.650 --> 00:19:22.010
this should be opened up to the whole of

318
00:19:22.050 --> 00:19:26.039
Aotearoa? Or what territories do you think that it should

319
00:19:26.070 --> 00:19:26.970
be open to?

320
00:19:28.020 --> 00:19:31.179
Well, I think it should be based on what the community feel, because I

321
00:19:32.030 --> 00:19:35.600
just think, like in the instance of our whānau and

322
00:19:35.650 --> 00:19:38.980
these tamariki, they live in multiple dwellings, and

323
00:19:39.670 --> 00:19:41.710
it should be opened up.

324
00:19:42.750 --> 00:19:44.440
Kia ora.

325
00:19:44.610 --> 00:19:47.710
All right. Hey, thank you, Lizzie. I really appreciate you coming on this morning.

326
00:19:47.750 --> 00:19:50.810
That's very nice. And it was a great presentation. Thank you.

327
00:19:51.190 --> 00:19:51.570
Thank you.

328
00:19:53.050 --> 00:19:55.810
Right. Now we're going to Clubs New Zealand.

329
00:19:56.130 --> 00:19:56.610
Lucy,

330
00:19:58.530 --> 00:19:59.590
are you with us, Lucy?

331
00:20:05.830 --> 00:20:07.970
All right. Good morning.

332
00:20:08.010 --> 00:20:10.210
Good morning. We're watching.

333
00:20:10.480 --> 00:20:10.480
Good morning.

334
00:20:10.510 --> 00:20:12.450
We are watching, and we've got 10 minutes with you.

335
00:20:12.470 --> 00:20:14.090
Looking forward to hearing what you've got to say.

336
00:20:14.670 --> 00:20:16.170
Brilliant. Thank you.

337
00:20:17.130 --> 00:20:17.270
And

338
00:20:18.270 --> 00:20:21.920
good morning, and thank you for the opportunity to appear today.

339
00:20:22.110 --> 00:20:25.870
My name is Lucy Wateriss, Chief Executive of Clubs New Zealand.

340
00:20:26.710 --> 00:20:29.850
We represent 300 clubs across the country,

341
00:20:30.570 --> 00:20:34.390
ranging from small groups of a few dozen members

342
00:20:34.450 --> 00:20:35.550
who might get together

343
00:20:36.450 --> 00:20:40.230
a few times a week, through to large community hubs of

344
00:20:40.310 --> 00:20:42.370
over 13,000 members.

345
00:20:43.290 --> 00:20:46.950
Regardless of size, they are places where New Zealanders gather to

346
00:20:47.010 --> 00:20:50.990
socialize, play sport, share meals, access

347
00:20:51.110 --> 00:20:54.270
affordable entertainment, and find community.

348
00:20:55.050 --> 00:20:56.890
Clubs New Zealand supports this bill.

349
00:20:57.830 --> 00:21:01.330
We think it strikes the right balance between harm minimization and

350
00:21:01.390 --> 00:21:04.750
practical improvements for responsible operators.

351
00:21:06.050 --> 00:21:09.910
Clubs are generally low risk. They are member-governed, not

352
00:21:09.990 --> 00:21:13.450
for profit, and deeply embedded within their communities.

353
00:21:13.980 --> 00:21:17.620
That model naturally supports responsible service, and it is a

354
00:21:17.650 --> 00:21:20.870
responsibility that we take seriously.

355
00:21:21.170 --> 00:21:25.050
As always, I take our written submission as read, and in the

356
00:21:25.110 --> 00:21:29.090
interest of time, want to focus today on why change is

357
00:21:29.130 --> 00:21:32.850
needed, particularly for club licenses and special licenses.

358
00:21:34.250 --> 00:21:37.790
The provision allowing clubs to choose between a club

359
00:21:37.850 --> 00:21:41.770
license and a non-license introduces something that clubs have not

360
00:21:41.830 --> 00:21:44.330
had in a very long time, and that is choice.

361
00:21:45.150 --> 00:21:47.180
We strongly support this provision.

362
00:21:47.770 --> 00:21:50.890
It provides a lawful and practical pathway for some

363
00:21:50.930 --> 00:21:54.470
clubs to better meet community needs.

364
00:21:54.510 --> 00:21:58.500
But it's important that it remains a genuine choice, and

365
00:21:58.590 --> 00:22:02.190
not something that clubs feel pushed toward by reporting

366
00:22:02.290 --> 00:22:05.830
agencies or because the existing settings are too

367
00:22:05.850 --> 00:22:06.690
restrictive.

368
00:22:07.970 --> 00:22:11.150
We do believe that clear transitional provisions

369
00:22:11.770 --> 00:22:14.370
need to be included within the bill.

370
00:22:14.430 --> 00:22:17.850
If a club chooses to move to a non-license,

371
00:22:18.310 --> 00:22:22.250
it should be treated as a transition, not a new license, and

372
00:22:22.330 --> 00:22:26.010
not a full reset. We do believe that its

373
00:22:26.030 --> 00:22:28.490
compliance history should be retained.

374
00:22:30.130 --> 00:22:31.450
While we strongly support

375
00:22:32.570 --> 00:22:35.890
clubs having the opportunity to choose between a club license and a

376
00:22:35.950 --> 00:22:39.850
non-license, we do believe that the underlying

377
00:22:39.970 --> 00:22:43.430
issues are found within Section 60 of the act

378
00:22:43.490 --> 00:22:46.030
itself, and they should be addressed as well.

379
00:22:47.250 --> 00:22:50.690
In our view, Section 60 is the root cause of the many

380
00:22:50.910 --> 00:22:52.910
challenges that clubs face today.

381
00:22:53.590 --> 00:22:57.150
It restricts who a club can serve in ways that no

382
00:22:57.350 --> 00:22:59.830
longer reflect how communities operate.

383
00:23:00.580 --> 00:23:04.490
That, in turn, limits a club's ability to host events, attract

384
00:23:04.570 --> 00:23:07.430
participation, and remain sustainable.

385
00:23:08.850 --> 00:23:11.930
Clubs today are not exclusive and closed

386
00:23:11.990 --> 00:23:15.710
environments. They are often the only venues for

387
00:23:15.750 --> 00:23:18.860
community events, such as funerals, prize givings,

388
00:23:18.990 --> 00:23:21.290
fundraisers, and local gatherings.

389
00:23:22.790 --> 00:23:26.590
300,000 New Zealanders choose to belong to one or more of our

390
00:23:26.630 --> 00:23:30.590
clubs, 4,000 people are employed within our clubs,

391
00:23:30.910 --> 00:23:34.850
and more than 6,000 volunteers give their time

392
00:23:34.930 --> 00:23:36.310
to our clubs every year.

393
00:23:37.450 --> 00:23:41.390
Yet to meet community expectations, clubs are often forced

394
00:23:41.510 --> 00:23:45.190
into what I would describe as complex workarounds of the law.

395
00:23:46.190 --> 00:23:49.770
It is the restrictive nature of Section 60 that drives heavy

396
00:23:49.810 --> 00:23:51.830
reliance on special licenses.

397
00:23:53.110 --> 00:23:57.030
And I do want to be clear that clubs are not applying for special licenses

398
00:23:57.090 --> 00:24:01.050
because they want to. They are doing so to meet community need and

399
00:24:01.090 --> 00:24:04.650
to comply with the law. This often means applying for special

400
00:24:04.710 --> 00:24:08.030
licenses for routine, low-risk events where alcohol is

401
00:24:08.070 --> 00:24:08.850
incidental.

402
00:24:09.770 --> 00:24:13.710
In some parts of the country, we've seen informal limits being applied

403
00:24:13.770 --> 00:24:17.510
to how many special licenses a club can apply for in one

404
00:24:17.590 --> 00:24:21.090
year. And you can just imagine the club

405
00:24:21.210 --> 00:24:25.110
newsletter going out, asking people to please delay their funerals or

406
00:24:25.120 --> 00:24:28.210
special occasions to the following year because the club

407
00:24:28.230 --> 00:24:31.110
has hit its special license limit.

408
00:24:32.190 --> 00:24:34.090
That sounds absurd to us, because it

409
00:24:34.130 --> 00:24:37.662
is.While it may sound

410
00:24:37.682 --> 00:24:41.612
macabre, funerals are actually a good example of where clubs

411
00:24:41.742 --> 00:24:45.482
use special licenses. That they're regularly

412
00:24:45.522 --> 00:24:49.382
hosting funerals for members of the club or the wider community,

413
00:24:49.982 --> 00:24:53.962
and in many cases, the club is such an important part

414
00:24:54.182 --> 00:24:57.622
of the member's life, it's where they choose to say farewell.

415
00:24:58.922 --> 00:25:02.362
But funerals are not events that we book weeks in advance,

416
00:25:02.802 --> 00:25:06.442
and the 20 working-day requirement for a special license is often

417
00:25:06.462 --> 00:25:10.442
impractical. And while waivers exist, they come

418
00:25:10.462 --> 00:25:13.842
with additional costs, and that adds stress

419
00:25:14.642 --> 00:25:17.922
and cost at an already difficult time for people.

420
00:25:18.942 --> 00:25:22.842
Another great example that I heard came from the House during the first reading

421
00:25:22.882 --> 00:25:25.152
of the bill. There was discussion

422
00:25:26.062 --> 00:25:30.022
around boating clubs needing special licenses for events like the Wotton Cup,

423
00:25:30.442 --> 00:25:33.942
where one club hosts another and another club visits.

424
00:25:33.982 --> 00:25:37.562
The issue here is not the participants in that boating event,

425
00:25:37.782 --> 00:25:38.422
it's the

426
00:25:39.442 --> 00:25:43.402
supporters, it's the family members, the friends, the wider community that turn

427
00:25:43.482 --> 00:25:47.262
up to support the event. Those people are often not members

428
00:25:47.302 --> 00:25:50.982
themselves of either clubs. So to remain

429
00:25:51.022 --> 00:25:54.842
compliant, the club is left with little choice but to apply for a

430
00:25:54.902 --> 00:25:58.722
special license to cover what is, in effect, a normal

431
00:25:58.962 --> 00:26:00.122
community activity.

432
00:26:01.222 --> 00:26:04.562
That is where the system becomes impractical because we're

433
00:26:04.802 --> 00:26:08.362
requiring already licensed low-risk clubs to

434
00:26:08.402 --> 00:26:12.322
repeatedly apply for special licenses for

435
00:26:12.382 --> 00:26:15.542
events that we believe pose no additional risk.

436
00:26:16.722 --> 00:26:20.342
We believe that there is a more practical approach through expanding the

437
00:26:20.382 --> 00:26:24.082
definition of authorized visitor under Section 60 to

438
00:26:24.122 --> 00:26:27.362
include any person attending a function or club event

439
00:26:27.802 --> 00:26:30.442
similar to jurisdictions like Queensland.

440
00:26:32.002 --> 00:26:35.512
Clubs are unique. We are not-for-profit, member-based

441
00:26:35.522 --> 00:26:39.122
community venues. But we are not immune to the pressures

442
00:26:39.222 --> 00:26:41.282
facing the wider hospitality sector.

443
00:26:42.142 --> 00:26:45.941
In my role, I'm often asked why are clubs struggling, why are RSAs

444
00:26:46.182 --> 00:26:46.691
folding.

445
00:26:47.562 --> 00:26:51.252
And the reality is, there is no one single answer to that, but

446
00:26:51.262 --> 00:26:55.222
perception plays a very big role. Imagine turning up

447
00:26:55.342 --> 00:26:58.882
to a club for the first time, being faced with a closed door, a

448
00:26:58.902 --> 00:27:02.171
doorbell, a swipe card access, a large members only

449
00:27:02.202 --> 00:27:06.002
sign. I myself have been chased across a club by the

450
00:27:06.062 --> 00:27:09.962
office lady. She was very well-intentioned, but asking me to sign the sign-in

451
00:27:10.022 --> 00:27:10.402
book.

452
00:27:11.352 --> 00:27:15.302
That is not welcoming, and it's a barrier before you've even stepped in the

453
00:27:15.342 --> 00:27:19.011
door. But those barriers exist because clubs are trying to comply with

454
00:27:19.182 --> 00:27:21.902
Section 60. At the same time, we

455
00:27:23.282 --> 00:27:26.942
are trying to evolve. We have clubs trying to introduce new membership

456
00:27:27.062 --> 00:27:30.962
categories. They are trying to be more open and accessible because

457
00:27:31.002 --> 00:27:33.702
they know they need to attract new members to survive.

458
00:27:34.482 --> 00:27:38.122
But too often those efforts are treated by reporting agencies with

459
00:27:38.202 --> 00:27:41.982
suspicion, or they're interpreted as attempts to work around the law.

460
00:27:42.982 --> 00:27:46.922
This creates a tension, and we need to rebalance the settings

461
00:27:46.982 --> 00:27:50.671
so that clubs can genuinely welcome people in so that

462
00:27:50.682 --> 00:27:54.582
becoming a member feels like a natural next step and not a

463
00:27:54.622 --> 00:27:58.562
compliance exercise. Because ultimately, if clubs

464
00:27:58.642 --> 00:28:02.002
cannot attract new members, they cannot remain sustainable.

465
00:28:02.542 --> 00:28:06.122
And if they're not sustainable, then we lose that really important

466
00:28:06.202 --> 00:28:08.842
community infrastructure that they provide.

467
00:28:09.862 --> 00:28:10.882
So in summary,

468
00:28:11.922 --> 00:28:15.822
we support this bill. We welcome the introduction of choice for clubs.

469
00:28:16.742 --> 00:28:20.042
But we strongly encourage the committee to ensure that there are fair

470
00:28:20.102 --> 00:28:23.622
transitional provisions for clubs that do choose a non-license.

471
00:28:24.482 --> 00:28:28.442
Amend Section 60 to better reflect how clubs operate today

472
00:28:28.502 --> 00:28:31.942
and address the practical realities of special licenses.

473
00:28:32.552 --> 00:28:35.822
These changes would reduce unnecessary burden, improve

474
00:28:35.922 --> 00:28:39.792
consistency, and ensure clubs can continue serving their communities in

475
00:28:39.942 --> 00:28:43.272
a safe and responsible way. Thank you.

476
00:28:43.302 --> 00:28:47.011
Hey, thanks, Lucy. Right. Questions, members? Right.

477
00:28:47.242 --> 00:28:48.882
Koharangi Kaa has got one.

478
00:28:49.942 --> 00:28:51.562
Thanks so much, Lucy.

479
00:28:52.782 --> 00:28:56.421
I'm just interested to know, in those 300 clubs,

480
00:28:57.942 --> 00:29:00.142
is it volunteers who are

481
00:29:01.302 --> 00:29:05.102
actually serving alcohol to

482
00:29:05.642 --> 00:29:07.182
members and their guests?

483
00:29:09.242 --> 00:29:10.072
In some of them-

484
00:29:10.072 --> 00:29:10.462
Some of them or all?

485
00:29:10.742 --> 00:29:14.342
Yes, it is. It largely depends on the size of the

486
00:29:14.382 --> 00:29:14.822
club.

487
00:29:15.462 --> 00:29:15.802
Yeah.

488
00:29:15.832 --> 00:29:16.222
So in

489
00:29:17.142 --> 00:29:20.862
the club with 13,000 members that I mentioned,

490
00:29:21.362 --> 00:29:23.992
they have paid staff that are all trained.

491
00:29:24.702 --> 00:29:28.552
However, in those smaller clubs where it might only be a couple of hundred members,

492
00:29:28.662 --> 00:29:30.942
then you're looking at volunteers.

493
00:29:31.402 --> 00:29:34.382
However, those volunteers are still all trained.

494
00:29:35.362 --> 00:29:39.342
There are roles within a club license where you don't

495
00:29:39.422 --> 00:29:41.122
have to have a duty manager

496
00:29:42.062 --> 00:29:45.662
on the premises at all times. However, we are

497
00:29:45.722 --> 00:29:49.242
finding that that is becoming a default condition that's

498
00:29:49.482 --> 00:29:51.442
placed on most club licenses.

499
00:29:51.962 --> 00:29:54.822
